She flipped to a blank page and wrote down the date. Beneath it, she wrote "11/05/648 - 13/12/648."
"Are you rereading memories?" asked Ivory, looking at the old notebook. Kari nodded. "Do you think they'll let you out for Christmas? It's only a few days away now."
Kari tapped twice on the lantern. No. Ivory had been right. The Ice King never let Kari out, because she was "a mistake" in his eyes. She was born mute, and she was the only girl in the family, otherwise entirely made up of boys.
Ivory was one too, in her own way. When she had stated her non-binary identity, it was as if the world had changed as well. She was given tasks that condemned her to solitude, as punishment for her difference.
Iel had to remain in service to the princess, but it wasn't too bad, because it gave iel a friend.
"It's almost your birthday, I think?" asked Ivory, remembering that the princess's birthday fell in a few days. Kari nodded, a sad gleam in her pale blue eyes.
"Do you want to celebrate it?" As iel asked the question, iel remembered what she had answered last time.
No, deflected Kari. Ivory knew it was a difficult subject for her. It was the day she had been confined to her room and her mother had been banished. Ivory was still a baby when it happened, but iel remembered the servants' and inhabitants' outrage. Iel had heard that Queen Eirwen was a good queen, but that she also had this strange ability to predict the future.
"Well... what do you want to do?" iel asked. Kari looked up with enthusiasm. She handed a piece of paper to Ivory. But when iel glanced at it...
Painting canvas 15 cm x 15 cm
White, several shades of blue paint
6 brushes of different sizes
Easel
"You want me to find these things for you?" asked Ivory, turning toward the silent princess who was frantically typing, shaking her pigtails back and forth. "Yes?" Iel chuckled slightly at the sight of the usually reserved princess becoming passionate about something. It was the first time she had asked for something unrelated to books and that wasn't in her room.
"Okay. See you later?" suggested Ivory, standing up and making her way through the pile of papers and notebooks.
Kari nodded and plunged back into her memories, wrapping herself once again in her thick comforter.
Iel left the room with relief. The princess was finally stepping out of her comfort zone by asking for things that weren't her responsibility, like paint.
Iel retraced their steps through the corridors, trying not to listen to the servants' whispers.
"I heard she's possessed by Queen Eirwen, that's why she always goes into that room."
"I heard she eats children in that room."
"She looks like a man, don't she?"
Iel covered their ears, because trying to ignore them wasn't working. Iel headed toward the royal painter's room, which was in the east wing, second door on the left.
Ivory approached the door, which was just as ornate as Kari's. It bore a white dragon, one of the 6 primordial dragons, who according to legend had created Frostfell. It was normal for the painter to display it on his door. He loved history.
Iel opened the door, expecting to find a normal scene. Paint splatters everywhere, pencils and papers scattered throughout the room, easels covering every last centimeter of wall. Surprisingly, iel saw none of that. The room was clean and there was a red velvet background with a stool just in front of it. On the stool stood Prince Aquilo, who was having his portrait painted.
"Ah, hello, Ivory! You come to watch your future king pose for a portrait?" Aquilo asked Ivory, giving them a wink.
"Pardon, little prince," iel replied, partially ignoring him, in search of the items that their silent friend desired. "I'm just here to get supplies."
"Ah, is the girl going to leave soon?" asked Aquilo, "But I wanted to see you!"
"Well, not me." Ivory had found the art supplies on their list and placed them in a box that iel had found. "And I'm not a girl."
The prince hadn't thought of that, however. "Oh my dear, you know well it's just a phase! It'll pass when you grow up!" he muttered.
"I have to go," iel said, suddenly uncomfortable, because of the prince's words, which reminded them of all the bad things people said about their gender identity. I want to get away from him.
"You're leaving already?" The Prince appeared at the door immediately, ignoring the painter's complaints.
"That's not the behavior of a future king!" iel scolded.
"No one will know. The others won't believe you, and the painter won't say anything if he values his life." He turned back to the painter for a second, then leaned toward Ivory. "What do you say to a romantic appointment?" Iel shuddered. Indeed, iel had received many threats in the past, but never from a prince, much less the heir to the throne.
"Don't you know what the word 'no' means?" iel said, pushing the prince aside.
"Hé no," replied Aquilo with a smile. Of course, the prince who gets everything he wants doesn't know what that word means.
Ivory rolled their eyes. "Why want a romantic appointment with me rather than with others? You must have a good hundred suitors?"
He interrupted them, still smiling: "500, to be exact." He flung his hair back, sending it flying through the cold air.
"Then, why me rather than another? I am the palace's threat." Iel wrapped their arms around their body.
"You are the most beautiful girl I have ever seen." Aquilo placed his finger under their chin and forced Ivory to look at him.
